{"formatVersion":"1","manifest":{"sourceId":"artOfWarEnglish","displayName":"The Art of War","type":"quotes","language":"English","edition":"Lionel Giles Translation","primaryCategory":"Philosophy & Thought","subcategory":"Strategy","audienceTags":["strategy","leadership"],"sortPriority":46,"itemCount":381,"supportsRandom":true,"supportsBrowse":true,"browseOrder":"sequence","groupingLevels":["chapter","section"],"groupingLabels":["Chapter","Section"],"dataPath":"Data/Collections/ArtOfWar_English.json","version":"1.0"},"data":[{"id":"artofwar-1-1","text":"Sun Tzŭ said: The art of war is of vital importance to the State.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 1.1","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"1","section":"1","chapterTitle":"Laying Plans"},"sequenceIndex":0},{"id":"artofwar-1-2","text":"It is a matter of life and death, a road either to safety or to ruin. Hence it is a subject of inquiry which can on no account be neglected.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 1.2","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"1","section":"2","chapterTitle":"Laying Plans"},"sequenceIndex":1},{"id":"artofwar-1-3","text":"The art of war, then, is governed by five constant factors, to be taken into account in one’s deliberations, when seeking to determine the conditions obtaining in the field.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 1.3","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"1","section":"3","chapterTitle":"Laying Plans"},"sequenceIndex":2},{"id":"artofwar-1-4","text":"These are: (1) The Moral Law; (2) Heaven; (3) Earth; (4) The Commander; (5) Method and discipline.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 1.4","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"1","section":"4","chapterTitle":"Laying Plans"},"sequenceIndex":3},{"id":"artofwar-1-5","text":"_The Moral Law_ causes the people to be in complete accord with","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 1.5","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"1","section":"5","chapterTitle":"Laying Plans"},"sequenceIndex":4},{"id":"artofwar-1-6","text":"_The Moral Law_ causes the people to be in complete accord with their ruler, so that they will follow him regardless of their lives, undismayed by any danger.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 1.6","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"1","section":"6","chapterTitle":"Laying Plans"},"sequenceIndex":5},{"id":"artofwar-1-7","text":"_Heaven_ signifies night and day, cold and heat, times and seasons.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 1.7","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"1","section":"7","chapterTitle":"Laying Plans"},"sequenceIndex":6},{"id":"artofwar-1-8","text":"_Earth_ comprises distances, great and small; danger and security; open ground and narrow passes; the chances of life and death.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 1.8","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"1","section":"8","chapterTitle":"Laying Plans"},"sequenceIndex":7},{"id":"artofwar-1-9","text":"_The Commander_ stands for the virtues of wisdom, sincerity, benevolence, courage and strictness.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 1.9","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"1","section":"9","chapterTitle":"Laying Plans"},"sequenceIndex":8},{"id":"artofwar-1-10","text":"By _Method and discipline_ are to be understood the marshalling of the army in its proper subdivisions, the gradations of rank among the officers, the maintenance of roads by which supplies may reach the army, and the control of military expenditure.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 1.10","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"1","section":"10","chapterTitle":"Laying Plans"},"sequenceIndex":9},{"id":"artofwar-1-11","text":"These five heads should be familiar to every general: he who knows them will be victorious; he who knows them not will fail.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 1.11","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"1","section":"11","chapterTitle":"Laying Plans"},"sequenceIndex":10},{"id":"artofwar-1-12","text":"Therefore, in your deliberations, when seeking to determine the military conditions, let them be made the basis of a comparison, in this wise:—","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 1.12","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"1","section":"12","chapterTitle":"Laying Plans"},"sequenceIndex":11},{"id":"artofwar-1-13","text":"(1) Which of the two sovereigns is imbued with the Moral law? (2) Which of the two generals has most ability? (3) With whom lie the advantages derived from Heaven and Earth? (4) On which side is discipline most rigorously enforced? (5) Which army is the stronger? (6) On which side are officers and men more highly trained? (7) In which army is there the greater constancy both in reward and punishment?","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 1.13","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"1","section":"13","chapterTitle":"Laying Plans"},"sequenceIndex":12},{"id":"artofwar-1-14","text":"By means of these seven considerations I can forecast victory or defeat.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 1.14","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"1","section":"14","chapterTitle":"Laying Plans"},"sequenceIndex":13},{"id":"artofwar-1-15","text":"The general that hearkens to my counsel and acts upon it, will conquer:—let such a one be retained in command! The general that hearkens not to my counsel nor acts upon it, will suffer defeat:—let such a one be dismissed!","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 1.15","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"1","section":"15","chapterTitle":"Laying Plans"},"sequenceIndex":14},{"id":"artofwar-1-16","text":"While heeding the profit of my counsel, avail yourself also of any helpful circumstances over and beyond the ordinary rules.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 1.16","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"1","section":"16","chapterTitle":"Laying Plans"},"sequenceIndex":15},{"id":"artofwar-1-17","text":"According as circumstances are favourable, one should modify one’s plans.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 1.17","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"1","section":"17","chapterTitle":"Laying Plans"},"sequenceIndex":16},{"id":"artofwar-1-18","text":"All warfare is based on deception.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 1.18","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"1","section":"18","chapterTitle":"Laying Plans"},"sequenceIndex":17},{"id":"artofwar-1-19","text":"Hence, when able to attack, we must seem unable; when using our forces, we must seem inactive; when we are near, we must make the enemy believe we are far away; when far away, we must make him believe we are near.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 1.19","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"1","section":"19","chapterTitle":"Laying Plans"},"sequenceIndex":18},{"id":"artofwar-1-20","text":"Hold out baits to entice the enemy. Feign disorder, and crush him.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 1.20","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"1","section":"20","chapterTitle":"Laying Plans"},"sequenceIndex":19},{"id":"artofwar-1-21","text":"If he is secure at all points, be prepared for him. If he is in superior strength, evade him.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 1.21","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"1","section":"21","chapterTitle":"Laying Plans"},"sequenceIndex":20},{"id":"artofwar-1-22","text":"If your opponent is of choleric temper, seek to irritate him. Pretend to be weak, that he may grow arrogant.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 1.22","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"1","section":"22","chapterTitle":"Laying Plans"},"sequenceIndex":21},{"id":"artofwar-1-23","text":"If he is taking his ease, give him no rest. If his forces are united, separate them.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 1.23","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"1","section":"23","chapterTitle":"Laying Plans"},"sequenceIndex":22},{"id":"artofwar-1-24","text":"Attack him where he is unprepared, appear where you are not expected.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 1.24","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"1","section":"24","chapterTitle":"Laying Plans"},"sequenceIndex":23},{"id":"artofwar-1-25","text":"These military devices, leading to victory, must not be divulged beforehand.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 1.25","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"1","section":"25","chapterTitle":"Laying Plans"},"sequenceIndex":24},{"id":"artofwar-1-26","text":"Now the general who wins a battle makes many calculations in his temple ere the battle is fought. The general who loses a battle makes but few calculations beforehand. Thus do many calculations lead to victory, and few calculations to defeat: how much more no calculation at all! It is by attention to this point that I can foresee who is likely to win or lose.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 1.26","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"1","section":"26","chapterTitle":"Laying Plans"},"sequenceIndex":25},{"id":"artofwar-2-1","text":"Sun Tzŭ said: In the operations of war, where there are in the field a thousand swift chariots, as many heavy chariots, and a hundred thousand mail-clad soldiers, with provisions enough to carry them a thousand _li_, the expenditure at home and at the front, including entertainment of guests, small items such as glue and paint, and sums spent on chariots and armour, will reach the total of a thousand ounces of silver per day. Such is the cost of raising an army of 100,000 men.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 2.1","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"2","section":"1","chapterTitle":"Waging War"},"sequenceIndex":26},{"id":"artofwar-2-2","text":"When you engage in actual fighting, if victory is long in coming, the men’s weapons will grow dull and their ardour will be damped. If you lay siege to a town, you will exhaust your strength.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 2.2","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"2","section":"2","chapterTitle":"Waging War"},"sequenceIndex":27},{"id":"artofwar-2-3","text":"Again, if the campaign is protracted, the resources of the State will not be equal to the strain.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 2.3","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"2","section":"3","chapterTitle":"Waging War"},"sequenceIndex":28},{"id":"artofwar-2-4","text":"Now, when your weapons are dulled, your ardour damped, your strength exhausted and your treasure spent, other chieftains will spring up to take advantage of your extremity. Then no man, however wise, will be able to avert the consequences that must ensue.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 2.4","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"2","section":"4","chapterTitle":"Waging War"},"sequenceIndex":29},{"id":"artofwar-2-5","text":"Thus, though we have heard of stupid haste in war, cleverness has never been seen associated with long delays.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 2.5","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"2","section":"5","chapterTitle":"Waging War"},"sequenceIndex":30},{"id":"artofwar-2-6","text":"There is no instance of a country having benefited from prolonged warfare.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 2.6","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"2","section":"6","chapterTitle":"Waging War"},"sequenceIndex":31},{"id":"artofwar-2-7","text":"It is only one who is thoroughly acquainted with the evils of war that can thoroughly understand the profitable way of carrying it on.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 2.7","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"2","section":"7","chapterTitle":"Waging War"},"sequenceIndex":32},{"id":"artofwar-2-8","text":"The skilful soldier does not raise a second levy, neither are his supply-waggons loaded more than twice.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 2.8","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"2","section":"8","chapterTitle":"Waging War"},"sequenceIndex":33},{"id":"artofwar-2-9","text":"Bring war material with you from home, but forage on the enemy. Thus the army will have food enough for its needs.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 2.9","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"2","section":"9","chapterTitle":"Waging War"},"sequenceIndex":34},{"id":"artofwar-2-10","text":"Poverty of the State exchequer causes an army to be maintained by contributions from a distance. Contributing to maintain an army at a distance causes the people to be impoverished.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 2.10","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"2","section":"10","chapterTitle":"Waging War"},"sequenceIndex":35},{"id":"artofwar-2-11","text":"On the other hand, the proximity of an army causes prices to go up; and high prices cause the people’s substance to be drained away.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 2.11","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"2","section":"11","chapterTitle":"Waging War"},"sequenceIndex":36},{"id":"artofwar-2-12","text":"When their substance is drained away, the peasantry will be afflicted by heavy exactions.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 2.12","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"2","section":"12","chapterTitle":"Waging War"},"sequenceIndex":37},{"id":"artofwar-2-13","text":"With this loss of substance and exhaustion of strength, the","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 2.13","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"2","section":"13","chapterTitle":"Waging War"},"sequenceIndex":38},{"id":"artofwar-2-14","text":"With this loss of substance and exhaustion of strength, the homes of the people will be stripped bare, and three-tenths of their incomes will be dissipated; while Government expenses for broken chariots, worn-out horses, breast-plates and helmets, bows and arrows, spears and shields, protective mantlets, draught-oxen and heavy waggons, will amount to four-tenths of its total revenue.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 2.14","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"2","section":"14","chapterTitle":"Waging War"},"sequenceIndex":39},{"id":"artofwar-2-15","text":"Hence a wise general makes a point of foraging on the enemy. One cartload of the enemy’s provisions is equivalent to twenty of one’s own, and likewise a single _picul_ of his provender is equivalent to twenty from one’s own store.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 2.15","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"2","section":"15","chapterTitle":"Waging War"},"sequenceIndex":40},{"id":"artofwar-2-16","text":"Now in order to kill the enemy, our men must be roused to anger; that there may be advantage from defeating the enemy, they must have their rewards.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 2.16","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"2","section":"16","chapterTitle":"Waging War"},"sequenceIndex":41},{"id":"artofwar-2-17","text":"Therefore in chariot fighting, when ten or more chariots have been taken, those should be rewarded who took the first. Our own flags should be substituted for those of the enemy, and the chariots mingled and used in conjunction with ours. The captured soldiers should be kindly treated and kept.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 2.17","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"2","section":"17","chapterTitle":"Waging War"},"sequenceIndex":42},{"id":"artofwar-2-18","text":"This is called, using the conquered foe to augment one’s own strength.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 2.18","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"2","section":"18","chapterTitle":"Waging War"},"sequenceIndex":43},{"id":"artofwar-2-19","text":"In war, then, let your great object be victory, not lengthy campaigns.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 2.19","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"2","section":"19","chapterTitle":"Waging War"},"sequenceIndex":44},{"id":"artofwar-2-20","text":"Thus it may be known that the leader of armies is the arbiter of the people’s fate, the man on whom it depends whether the nation shall be in peace or in peril.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 2.20","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"2","section":"20","chapterTitle":"Waging War"},"sequenceIndex":45},{"id":"artofwar-3-1","text":"Sun Tzŭ said: In the practical art of war, the best thing of all is to take the enemy’s country whole and intact; to shatter and destroy it is not so good. So, too, it is better to capture an army entire than to destroy it, to capture a regiment, a detachment or a company entire than to destroy them.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 3.1","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"3","section":"1","chapterTitle":"Attack By Stratagem"},"sequenceIndex":46},{"id":"artofwar-3-2","text":"Hence to fight and conquer in all your battles is not supreme excellence; supreme excellence consists in breaking the enemy’s resistance without fighting.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 3.2","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"3","section":"2","chapterTitle":"Attack By Stratagem"},"sequenceIndex":47},{"id":"artofwar-3-3","text":"Thus the highest form of generalship is to baulk the enemy’s plans; the next best is to prevent the junction of the enemy’s forces; the next in order is to attack the enemy’s army in the field; and the worst policy of all is to besiege walled cities.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 3.3","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"3","section":"3","chapterTitle":"Attack By Stratagem"},"sequenceIndex":48},{"id":"artofwar-3-4","text":"The rule is, not to besiege walled cities if it can possibly be avoided. The preparation of mantlets, movable shelters, and various implements of war, will take up three whole months; and the piling up of mounds over against the walls will take three months more.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 3.4","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"3","section":"4","chapterTitle":"Attack By Stratagem"},"sequenceIndex":49},{"id":"artofwar-3-5","text":"The general, unable to control his irritation, will launch his men to the assault like swarming ants, with the result that one-third of his men are slain, while the town still remains untaken. Such are the disastrous effects of a siege.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 3.5","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"3","section":"5","chapterTitle":"Attack By Stratagem"},"sequenceIndex":50},{"id":"artofwar-3-6","text":"Therefore the skilful leader subdues the enemy’s troops without any fighting; he captures their cities without laying siege to them; he overthrows their kingdom without lengthy operations in the field.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 3.6","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"3","section":"6","chapterTitle":"Attack By Stratagem"},"sequenceIndex":51},{"id":"artofwar-3-7","text":"With his forces intact he will dispute the mastery of the Empire, and thus, without losing a man, his triumph will be complete. This is the method of attacking by stratagem.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 3.7","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"3","section":"7","chapterTitle":"Attack By Stratagem"},"sequenceIndex":52},{"id":"artofwar-3-8","text":"It is the rule in war, if our forces are ten to the enemy’s one, to surround him; if five to one, to attack him; if twice as numerous, to divide our army into two.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 3.8","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"3","section":"8","chapterTitle":"Attack By Stratagem"},"sequenceIndex":53},{"id":"artofwar-3-9","text":"If equally matched, we can offer battle; if slightly inferior in numbers, we can avoid the enemy; if quite unequal in every way, we can flee from him.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 3.9","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"3","section":"9","chapterTitle":"Attack By Stratagem"},"sequenceIndex":54},{"id":"artofwar-3-10","text":"Hence, though an obstinate fight may be made by a small force, in the end it must be captured by the larger force.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 3.10","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"3","section":"10","chapterTitle":"Attack By Stratagem"},"sequenceIndex":55},{"id":"artofwar-3-11","text":"Now the general is the bulwark of the State: if the bulwark is complete at all points; the State will be strong; if the bulwark is defective, the State will be weak.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 3.11","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"3","section":"11","chapterTitle":"Attack By Stratagem"},"sequenceIndex":56},{"id":"artofwar-3-12","text":"There are three ways in which a ruler can bring misfortune upon his army:—","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 3.12","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"3","section":"12","chapterTitle":"Attack By Stratagem"},"sequenceIndex":57},{"id":"artofwar-3-13","text":"(1) By commanding the army to advance or to retreat, being ignorant of the fact that it cannot obey. This is called hobbling the army.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 3.13","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"3","section":"13","chapterTitle":"Attack By Stratagem"},"sequenceIndex":58},{"id":"artofwar-3-14","text":"(2) By attempting to govern an army in the same way as he administers a kingdom, being ignorant of the conditions which obtain in an army. This causes restlessness in the soldier’s minds.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 3.14","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"3","section":"14","chapterTitle":"Attack By Stratagem"},"sequenceIndex":59},{"id":"artofwar-3-15","text":"(3) By employing the officers of his army without discrimination, through ignorance of the military principle of adaptation to circumstances. This shakes the confidence of the soldiers.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 3.15","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"3","section":"15","chapterTitle":"Attack By Stratagem"},"sequenceIndex":60},{"id":"artofwar-3-16","text":"But when the army is restless and distrustful, trouble is sure to come from the other feudal princes. This is simply bringing anarchy into the army, and flinging victory away.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 3.16","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"3","section":"16","chapterTitle":"Attack By Stratagem"},"sequenceIndex":61},{"id":"artofwar-3-17","text":"Thus we may know that there are five essentials for victory: (1) He will win who knows when to fight and when not to fight. (2) He will win who knows how to handle both superior and inferior forces. (3) He will win whose army is animated by the same spirit throughout all its ranks. (4) He will win who, prepared himself, waits to take the enemy unprepared. (5) He will win who has military capacity and is not interfered with by the sovereign. Victory lies in the knowledge of these five points.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 3.17","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"3","section":"17","chapterTitle":"Attack By Stratagem"},"sequenceIndex":62},{"id":"artofwar-3-18","text":"Hence the saying: If you know the enemy and know yourself, you need not fear the result of a hundred battles. If you know yourself but not the enemy, for every victory gained you will also suffer a defeat. If you know neither the enemy nor yourself, you will succumb in every battle.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 3.18","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"3","section":"18","chapterTitle":"Attack By Stratagem"},"sequenceIndex":63},{"id":"artofwar-4-1","text":"Sun Tzŭ said: The good fighters of old first put themselves beyond the possibility of defeat, and then waited for an opportunity of defeating the enemy.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 4.1","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"4","section":"1","chapterTitle":"Tactical Dispositions"},"sequenceIndex":64},{"id":"artofwar-4-2","text":"To secure ourselves against defeat lies in our own hands, but the opportunity of defeating the enemy is provided by the enemy himself.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 4.2","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"4","section":"2","chapterTitle":"Tactical Dispositions"},"sequenceIndex":65},{"id":"artofwar-4-3","text":"Thus the good fighter is able to secure himself against defeat, but cannot make certain of defeating the enemy.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 4.3","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"4","section":"3","chapterTitle":"Tactical Dispositions"},"sequenceIndex":66},{"id":"artofwar-4-4","text":"Hence the saying: One may _know_ how to conquer without being able to _do_ it.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 4.4","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"4","section":"4","chapterTitle":"Tactical Dispositions"},"sequenceIndex":67},{"id":"artofwar-4-5","text":"Security against defeat implies defensive tactics; ability to defeat the enemy means taking the offensive.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 4.5","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"4","section":"5","chapterTitle":"Tactical Dispositions"},"sequenceIndex":68},{"id":"artofwar-4-6","text":"Standing on the defensive indicates insufficient strength; attacking, a superabundance of strength.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 4.6","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"4","section":"6","chapterTitle":"Tactical Dispositions"},"sequenceIndex":69},{"id":"artofwar-4-7","text":"The general who is skilled in defence hides in the most secret recesses of the earth; he who is skilled in attack flashes forth from the topmost heights of heaven. Thus on the one hand we have ability to protect ourselves; on the other, a victory that is complete.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 4.7","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"4","section":"7","chapterTitle":"Tactical Dispositions"},"sequenceIndex":70},{"id":"artofwar-4-8","text":"To see victory only when it is within the ken of the common herd is not the acme of excellence.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 4.8","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"4","section":"8","chapterTitle":"Tactical Dispositions"},"sequenceIndex":71},{"id":"artofwar-4-9","text":"Neither is it the acme of excellence if you fight and conquer and the whole Empire says, \"Well done!\" to see sun and moon is no sign of sharp sight; to hear the noise of thunder is no sign of a quick ear.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 4.9","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"4","section":"9","chapterTitle":"Tactical Dispositions"},"sequenceIndex":72},{"id":"artofwar-4-11","text":"What the ancients called a clever fighter is one who not only wins, but excels in winning with ease.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 4.11","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"4","section":"11","chapterTitle":"Tactical Dispositions"},"sequenceIndex":73},{"id":"artofwar-4-12","text":"Hence his victories bring him neither reputation for wisdom nor credit for courage.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 4.12","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"4","section":"12","chapterTitle":"Tactical Dispositions"},"sequenceIndex":74},{"id":"artofwar-4-13","text":"He wins his battles by making no mistakes. Making no mistakes is what establishes the certainty of victory, for it means conquering an enemy that is already defeated.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 4.13","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"4","section":"13","chapterTitle":"Tactical Dispositions"},"sequenceIndex":75},{"id":"artofwar-4-14","text":"Hence the skilful fighter puts himself into a position which makes defeat impossible, and does not miss the moment for defeating the enemy.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 4.14","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"4","section":"14","chapterTitle":"Tactical Dispositions"},"sequenceIndex":76},{"id":"artofwar-4-15","text":"Thus it is that in war the victorious strategist only seeks battle after the victory has been won, whereas he who is destined to defeat first fights and afterwards looks for victory.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 4.15","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"4","section":"15","chapterTitle":"Tactical Dispositions"},"sequenceIndex":77},{"id":"artofwar-4-16","text":"The consummate leader cultivates the moral law, and strictly adheres to method and discipline; thus it is in his power to control success.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 4.16","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"4","section":"16","chapterTitle":"Tactical Dispositions"},"sequenceIndex":78},{"id":"artofwar-4-17","text":"In respect of military method, we have, firstly, Measurement; secondly, Estimation of quantity; thirdly, Calculation; fourthly, Balancing of chances; fifthly, Victory.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 4.17","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"4","section":"17","chapterTitle":"Tactical Dispositions"},"sequenceIndex":79},{"id":"artofwar-4-18","text":"Measurement owes its existence to Earth; Estimation of quantity to Measurement; Calculation to Estimation of quantity; Balancing of chances to Calculation; and Victory to Balancing of chances.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 4.18","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"4","section":"18","chapterTitle":"Tactical Dispositions"},"sequenceIndex":80},{"id":"artofwar-4-19","text":"A victorious army opposed to a routed one, is as a pound’s weight placed in the scale against a single grain.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 4.19","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"4","section":"19","chapterTitle":"Tactical Dispositions"},"sequenceIndex":81},{"id":"artofwar-4-20","text":"The onrush of a conquering force is like the bursting of pent-up waters into a chasm a thousand fathoms deep. So much for tactical dispositions.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 4.20","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"4","section":"20","chapterTitle":"Tactical Dispositions"},"sequenceIndex":82},{"id":"artofwar-5-1","text":"Sun Tzŭ said: The control of a large force is the same principle as the control of a few men: it is merely a question of dividing up their numbers.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 5.1","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"5","section":"1","chapterTitle":"Energy"},"sequenceIndex":83},{"id":"artofwar-5-2","text":"Fighting with a large army under your command is nowise different from fighting with a small one: it is merely a question of instituting signs and signals.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 5.2","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"5","section":"2","chapterTitle":"Energy"},"sequenceIndex":84},{"id":"artofwar-5-3","text":"To ensure that your whole host may withstand the brunt of the enemy’s attack and remain unshaken—this is effected by manœuvers direct and indirect.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 5.3","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"5","section":"3","chapterTitle":"Energy"},"sequenceIndex":85},{"id":"artofwar-5-4","text":"That the impact of your army may be like a grindstone dashed against an egg—this is effected by the science of weak points and strong.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 5.4","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"5","section":"4","chapterTitle":"Energy"},"sequenceIndex":86},{"id":"artofwar-5-5","text":"In all fighting, the direct method may be used for joining battle, but indirect methods will be needed in order to secure victory.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 5.5","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"5","section":"5","chapterTitle":"Energy"},"sequenceIndex":87},{"id":"artofwar-5-6","text":"Indirect tactics, efficiently applied, are inexhausible as Heaven and Earth, unending as the flow of rivers and streams; like the sun and moon, they end but to begin anew; like the four seasons, they pass away but to return once more.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 5.6","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"5","section":"6","chapterTitle":"Energy"},"sequenceIndex":88},{"id":"artofwar-5-7","text":"There are not more than five musical notes, yet the combinations of these five give rise to more melodies than can ever be heard.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 5.7","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"5","section":"7","chapterTitle":"Energy"},"sequenceIndex":89},{"id":"artofwar-5-8","text":"There are not more than five primary colours (blue, yellow, red, white, and black), yet in combination they produce more hues than can ever be seen. 9 There are not more than five cardinal tastes (sour, acrid, salt, sweet, bitter), yet combinations of them yield more flavours than can ever be tasted.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 5.8","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"5","section":"8","chapterTitle":"Energy"},"sequenceIndex":90},{"id":"artofwar-5-10","text":"In battle, there are not more than two methods of attack—the direct and the indirect; yet these two in combination give rise to an endless series of manœuvers.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 5.10","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"5","section":"10","chapterTitle":"Energy"},"sequenceIndex":91},{"id":"artofwar-5-11","text":"The direct and the indirect lead on to each other in turn. It is like moving in a circle—you never come to an end. Who can exhaust the possibilities of their combination?","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 5.11","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"5","section":"11","chapterTitle":"Energy"},"sequenceIndex":92},{"id":"artofwar-5-12","text":"The onset of troops is like the rush of a torrent which will even roll stones along in its course.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 5.12","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"5","section":"12","chapterTitle":"Energy"},"sequenceIndex":93},{"id":"artofwar-5-13","text":"The quality of decision is like the well-timed swoop of a falcon which enables it to strike and destroy its victim.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 5.13","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"5","section":"13","chapterTitle":"Energy"},"sequenceIndex":94},{"id":"artofwar-5-14","text":"Therefore the good fighter will be terrible in his onset, and prompt in his decision.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 5.14","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"5","section":"14","chapterTitle":"Energy"},"sequenceIndex":95},{"id":"artofwar-5-15","text":"Energy may be likened to the bending of a crossbow; decision, to the releasing of the trigger.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 5.15","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"5","section":"15","chapterTitle":"Energy"},"sequenceIndex":96},{"id":"artofwar-5-16","text":"Amid the turmoil and tumult of battle, there may be seeming disorder and yet no real disorder at all; amid confusion and chaos, your array may be without head or tail, yet it will be proof against defeat.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 5.16","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"5","section":"16","chapterTitle":"Energy"},"sequenceIndex":97},{"id":"artofwar-5-17","text":"Simulated disorder postulates perfect discipline; simulated fear postulates courage; simulated weakness postulates strength.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 5.17","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"5","section":"17","chapterTitle":"Energy"},"sequenceIndex":98},{"id":"artofwar-5-18","text":"Hiding order beneath the cloak of disorder is simply a question of subdivision; concealing courage under a show of timidity presupposes a fund of latent energy; masking strength with weakness is to be effected by tactical dispositions.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 5.18","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"5","section":"18","chapterTitle":"Energy"},"sequenceIndex":99},{"id":"artofwar-5-19","text":"Thus one who is skilful at keeping the enemy on the move maintains deceitful appearances, according to which the enemy will act. He sacrifices something, that the enemy may snatch at it.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 5.19","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"5","section":"19","chapterTitle":"Energy"},"sequenceIndex":100},{"id":"artofwar-5-20","text":"By holding out baits, he keeps him on the march; then with a body of picked men he lies in wait for him.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 5.20","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"5","section":"20","chapterTitle":"Energy"},"sequenceIndex":101},{"id":"artofwar-5-21","text":"The clever combatant looks to the effect of combined energy, and does not require too much from individuals. Hence his ability to pick out the right men and utilise combined energy.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 5.21","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"5","section":"21","chapterTitle":"Energy"},"sequenceIndex":102},{"id":"artofwar-5-22","text":"When he utilises combined energy, his fighting men become as it were like unto rolling logs or stones. For it is the nature of a log or stone to remain motionless on level ground, and to move when on a slope; if four-cornered, to come to a standstill, but if round-shaped, to go rolling down.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 5.22","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"5","section":"22","chapterTitle":"Energy"},"sequenceIndex":103},{"id":"artofwar-5-23","text":"Thus the energy developed by good fighting men is as the momentum of a round stone rolled down a mountain thousands of feet in height. So much on the subject of energy.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 5.23","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"5","section":"23","chapterTitle":"Energy"},"sequenceIndex":104},{"id":"artofwar-6-1","text":"Sun Tzŭ said: Whoever is first in the field and awaits the coming of the enemy, will be fresh for the fight; whoever is second in the field and has to hasten to battle, will arrive exhausted.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 6.1","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"6","section":"1","chapterTitle":"Weak Points And Strong"},"sequenceIndex":105},{"id":"artofwar-6-2","text":"Therefore the clever combatant imposes his will on the enemy, but does not allow the enemy’s will to be imposed on him.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 6.2","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"6","section":"2","chapterTitle":"Weak Points And Strong"},"sequenceIndex":106},{"id":"artofwar-6-3","text":"By holding out advantages to him, he can cause the enemy to approach of his own accord; or, by inflicting damage, he can make it impossible for the enemy to draw near.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 6.3","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"6","section":"3","chapterTitle":"Weak Points And Strong"},"sequenceIndex":107},{"id":"artofwar-6-4","text":"If the enemy is taking his ease, he can harass him; if well supplied with food, he can starve him out; if quietly encamped, he can force him to move.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 6.4","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"6","section":"4","chapterTitle":"Weak Points And Strong"},"sequenceIndex":108},{"id":"artofwar-6-5","text":"Appear at points which the enemy must hasten to defend; march swiftly to places where you are not expected.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 6.5","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"6","section":"5","chapterTitle":"Weak Points And Strong"},"sequenceIndex":109},{"id":"artofwar-6-6","text":"An army may march great distances without distress, if it marches through country where the enemy is not.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 6.6","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"6","section":"6","chapterTitle":"Weak Points And Strong"},"sequenceIndex":110},{"id":"artofwar-6-7","text":"You can be sure of succeeding in your attacks if you only attack places which are undefended. You can ensure the safety of your defence if you only hold positions that cannot be attacked.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 6.7","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"6","section":"7","chapterTitle":"Weak Points And Strong"},"sequenceIndex":111},{"id":"artofwar-6-8","text":"Hence that general is skilful in attack whose opponent does not know what to defend; and he is skilful in defence whose opponent does not know what to attack.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 6.8","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"6","section":"8","chapterTitle":"Weak Points And Strong"},"sequenceIndex":112},{"id":"artofwar-6-9","text":"O divine art of subtlety and secrecy! Through you we learn to be invisible, through you inaudible; and hence we can hold the enemy’s fate in our hands.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 6.9","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"6","section":"9","chapterTitle":"Weak Points And Strong"},"sequenceIndex":113},{"id":"artofwar-6-10","text":"You may advance and be absolutely irresistible, if you make for the enemy’s weak points; you may retire and be safe from pursuit if your movements are more rapid than those of the enemy.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 6.10","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"6","section":"10","chapterTitle":"Weak Points And Strong"},"sequenceIndex":114},{"id":"artofwar-6-11","text":"If we wish to fight, the enemy can be forced to an engagement even though he be sheltered behind a high rampart and a deep ditch. All we need do is attack some other place that he will be obliged to relieve.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 6.11","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"6","section":"11","chapterTitle":"Weak Points And Strong"},"sequenceIndex":115},{"id":"artofwar-6-12","text":"If we do not wish to fight, we can prevent the enemy from engaging us even though the lines of our encampment be merely traced out on the ground. All we need do is to throw something odd and unaccountable in his way.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 6.12","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"6","section":"12","chapterTitle":"Weak Points And Strong"},"sequenceIndex":116},{"id":"artofwar-6-13","text":"By discovering the enemy’s dispositions and remaining invisible ourselves, we can keep our forces concentrated, while the enemy’s must be divided.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 6.13","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"6","section":"13","chapterTitle":"Weak Points And Strong"},"sequenceIndex":117},{"id":"artofwar-6-14","text":"We can form a single united body, while the enemy must split up into fractions. Hence there will be a whole pitted against separate parts of a whole, which means that we shall be many to the enemy’s few.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 6.14","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"6","section":"14","chapterTitle":"Weak Points And Strong"},"sequenceIndex":118},{"id":"artofwar-6-15","text":"And if we are able thus to attack an inferior force with a superior one, our opponents will be in dire straits.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 6.15","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"6","section":"15","chapterTitle":"Weak Points And Strong"},"sequenceIndex":119},{"id":"artofwar-6-16","text":"The spot where we intend to fight must not be made known; for then the enemy will have to prepare against a possible attack at several different points; and his forces being thus distributed in many directions, the numbers we shall have to face at any given point will be proportionately few.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 6.16","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"6","section":"16","chapterTitle":"Weak Points And Strong"},"sequenceIndex":120},{"id":"artofwar-6-17","text":"For should the enemy strengthen his van, he will weaken his rear; should he strengthen his rear, he will weaken his van; should he strengthen his left, he will weaken his right; should he strengthen his right, he will weaken his left. If he sends reinforcements everywhere, he will everywhere be weak.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 6.17","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"6","section":"17","chapterTitle":"Weak Points And Strong"},"sequenceIndex":121},{"id":"artofwar-6-18","text":"Numerical weakness comes from having to prepare against possible attacks; numerical strength, from compelling our adversary to make these preparations against us.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 6.18","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"6","section":"18","chapterTitle":"Weak Points And Strong"},"sequenceIndex":122},{"id":"artofwar-6-19","text":"Knowing the place and the time of the coming battle, we may concentrate from the greatest distances in order to fight.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 6.19","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"6","section":"19","chapterTitle":"Weak Points And Strong"},"sequenceIndex":123},{"id":"artofwar-6-20","text":"But if neither time nor place be known, then the left wing will be impotent to succour the right, the right equally impotent to succour the left, the van unable to relieve the rear, or the rear to support the van. How much more so if the furthest portions of the army are anything under a hundred _li_ apart, and even the nearest are separated by several _li_!","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 6.20","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"6","section":"20","chapterTitle":"Weak Points And Strong"},"sequenceIndex":124},{"id":"artofwar-6-21","text":"Though according to my estimate the soldiers of Yüeh exceed our own in number, that shall advantage them nothing in the matter of victory. I say then that victory can be achieved.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 6.21","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"6","section":"21","chapterTitle":"Weak Points And Strong"},"sequenceIndex":125},{"id":"artofwar-6-22","text":"Though the enemy be stronger in numbers, we may prevent him from fighting. Scheme so as to discover his plans and the likelihood of their success. Force him to reveal himself, so as to find out his vulnerable spots.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 6.22","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"6","section":"22","chapterTitle":"Weak Points And Strong"},"sequenceIndex":126},{"id":"artofwar-6-24","text":"Carefully compare the opposing army with your own, so that you may know where strength is superabundant and where it is deficient.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 6.24","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"6","section":"24","chapterTitle":"Weak Points And Strong"},"sequenceIndex":127},{"id":"artofwar-6-25","text":"In making tactical dispositions, the highest pitch you can attain is to conceal them; conceal your dispositions, and you will be safe from the prying of the subtlest spies, from the machinations of the wisest brains.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 6.25","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"6","section":"25","chapterTitle":"Weak Points And Strong"},"sequenceIndex":128},{"id":"artofwar-6-26","text":"How victory may be produced for them out of the enemy’s own tactics—that is what the multitude cannot comprehend.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 6.26","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"6","section":"26","chapterTitle":"Weak Points And Strong"},"sequenceIndex":129},{"id":"artofwar-6-27","text":"All men can see the tactics whereby I conquer, but what none can see is the strategy out of which victory is evolved.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 6.27","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"6","section":"27","chapterTitle":"Weak Points And Strong"},"sequenceIndex":130},{"id":"artofwar-6-28","text":"Do not repeat the tactics which have gained you one victory, but let your methods be regulated by the infinite variety of circumstances.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 6.28","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"6","section":"28","chapterTitle":"Weak Points And Strong"},"sequenceIndex":131},{"id":"artofwar-6-29","text":"Military tactics are like unto water; for water in its natural course runs away from high places and hastens downwards.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 6.29","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"6","section":"29","chapterTitle":"Weak Points And Strong"},"sequenceIndex":132},{"id":"artofwar-6-30","text":"So in war, the way is to avoid what is strong and to strike at what is weak.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 6.30","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"6","section":"30","chapterTitle":"Weak Points And Strong"},"sequenceIndex":133},{"id":"artofwar-6-31","text":"Water shapes its course according to the nature of the ground over which it flows; the soldier works out his victory in relation to the foe whom he is facing.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 6.31","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"6","section":"31","chapterTitle":"Weak Points And Strong"},"sequenceIndex":134},{"id":"artofwar-6-32","text":"Therefore, just as water retains no constant shape, so in warfare there are no constant conditions.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 6.32","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"6","section":"32","chapterTitle":"Weak Points And Strong"},"sequenceIndex":135},{"id":"artofwar-6-33","text":"He who can modify his tactics in relation to his opponent and thereby succeed in winning, may be called a heaven-born captain.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 6.33","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"6","section":"33","chapterTitle":"Weak Points And Strong"},"sequenceIndex":136},{"id":"artofwar-6-34","text":"The five elements (water, fire, wood, metal, earth) are not always equally predominant; the four seasons make way for each other in turn. There are short days and long; the moon has its periods of waning and waxing.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 6.34","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"6","section":"34","chapterTitle":"Weak Points And Strong"},"sequenceIndex":137},{"id":"artofwar-7-1","text":"Sun Tzŭ said: In war, the general receives his commands from the sovereign.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 7.1","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"7","section":"1","chapterTitle":"Manœuvering"},"sequenceIndex":138},{"id":"artofwar-7-2","text":"Having collected an army and concentrated his forces, he must blend and harmonise the different elements thereof before pitching his camp.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 7.2","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"7","section":"2","chapterTitle":"Manœuvering"},"sequenceIndex":139},{"id":"artofwar-7-3","text":"After that, comes tactical manœuvering, than which there is nothing more difficult. The difficulty of tactical manœuvering consists in turning the devious into the direct, and misfortune into gain.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 7.3","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"7","section":"3","chapterTitle":"Manœuvering"},"sequenceIndex":140},{"id":"artofwar-7-4","text":"Thus, to take a long and circuitous route, after enticing the enemy out of the way, and though starting after him, to contrive to reach the goal before him, shows knowledge of the artifice of _deviation_.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 7.4","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"7","section":"4","chapterTitle":"Manœuvering"},"sequenceIndex":141},{"id":"artofwar-7-5","text":"Manœuvering with an army is advantageous; with an undisciplined multitude, most dangerous.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 7.5","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"7","section":"5","chapterTitle":"Manœuvering"},"sequenceIndex":142},{"id":"artofwar-7-6","text":"If you set a fully equipped army in march in order to snatch an advantage, the chances are that you will be too late. On the other hand, to detach a flying column for the purpose involves the sacrifice of its baggage and stores.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 7.6","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"7","section":"6","chapterTitle":"Manœuvering"},"sequenceIndex":143},{"id":"artofwar-7-7","text":"Thus, if you order your men to roll up their buff-coats, and make forced marches without halting day or night, covering double the usual distance at a stretch, doing a hundred _li_ in order to wrest an advantage, the leaders of all your three divisions will fall into the hands of the enemy.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 7.7","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"7","section":"7","chapterTitle":"Manœuvering"},"sequenceIndex":144},{"id":"artofwar-7-8","text":"The stronger men will be in front, the jaded ones will fall behind, and on this plan only one-tenth of your army will reach its destination.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 7.8","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"7","section":"8","chapterTitle":"Manœuvering"},"sequenceIndex":145},{"id":"artofwar-7-9","text":"If you march fifty _li_ in order to outmanœuver the enemy, you will lose the leader of your first division, and only half your force will reach the goal.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 7.9","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"7","section":"9","chapterTitle":"Manœuvering"},"sequenceIndex":146},{"id":"artofwar-7-10","text":"If you march thirty _li_ with the same object, two-thirds of your army will arrive.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 7.10","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"7","section":"10","chapterTitle":"Manœuvering"},"sequenceIndex":147},{"id":"artofwar-7-11","text":"We may take it then that an army without its baggage-train is lost; without provisions it is lost; without bases of supply it is lost.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 7.11","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"7","section":"11","chapterTitle":"Manœuvering"},"sequenceIndex":148},{"id":"artofwar-7-12","text":"We cannot enter into alliances until we are acquainted with the designs of our neighbours.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 7.12","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"7","section":"12","chapterTitle":"Manœuvering"},"sequenceIndex":149},{"id":"artofwar-7-13","text":"We are not fit to lead an army on the march unless we are familiar with the face of the country—its mountains and forests, its pitfalls and precipices, its marshes and swamps.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 7.13","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"7","section":"13","chapterTitle":"Manœuvering"},"sequenceIndex":150},{"id":"artofwar-7-14","text":"We shall be unable to turn natural advantages to account unless we make use of local guides.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 7.14","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"7","section":"14","chapterTitle":"Manœuvering"},"sequenceIndex":151},{"id":"artofwar-7-15","text":"In war, practise dissimulation, and you will succeed. Move only if there is a real advantage to be gained.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 7.15","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"7","section":"15","chapterTitle":"Manœuvering"},"sequenceIndex":152},{"id":"artofwar-7-16","text":"Whether to concentrate or to divide your troops, must be decided by circumstances.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 7.16","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"7","section":"16","chapterTitle":"Manœuvering"},"sequenceIndex":153},{"id":"artofwar-7-17","text":"Let your rapidity be that of the wind, your compactness that of the forest.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 7.17","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"7","section":"17","chapterTitle":"Manœuvering"},"sequenceIndex":154},{"id":"artofwar-7-18","text":"In raiding and plundering be like fire, in immovability like a mountain.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 7.18","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"7","section":"18","chapterTitle":"Manœuvering"},"sequenceIndex":155},{"id":"artofwar-7-19","text":"Let your plans be dark and impenetrable as night, and when you move, fall like a thunderbolt.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 7.19","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"7","section":"19","chapterTitle":"Manœuvering"},"sequenceIndex":156},{"id":"artofwar-7-20","text":"When you plunder a countryside, let the spoil be divided amongst your men; when you capture new territory, cut it up into allotments for the benefit of the soldiery.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 7.20","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"7","section":"20","chapterTitle":"Manœuvering"},"sequenceIndex":157},{"id":"artofwar-7-21","text":"Ponder and deliberate before you make a move.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 7.21","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"7","section":"21","chapterTitle":"Manœuvering"},"sequenceIndex":158},{"id":"artofwar-7-22","text":"He will conquer who has learnt the artifice of deviation. Such is the art of manœuvering.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 7.22","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"7","section":"22","chapterTitle":"Manœuvering"},"sequenceIndex":159},{"id":"artofwar-7-23","text":"The Book of Army Management says: On the field of battle, the spoken word does not carry far enough: hence the institution of gongs and drums. Nor can ordinary objects be seen clearly enough: hence the institution of banners and flags.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 7.23","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"7","section":"23","chapterTitle":"Manœuvering"},"sequenceIndex":160},{"id":"artofwar-7-24","text":"Gongs and drums, banners and flags, are means whereby the ears and eyes of the host may be focussed on one particular point.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 7.24","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"7","section":"24","chapterTitle":"Manœuvering"},"sequenceIndex":161},{"id":"artofwar-7-25","text":"The host thus forming a single united body, is it impossible either for the brave to advance alone, or for the cowardly to retreat alone. This is the art of handling large masses of men.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 7.25","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"7","section":"25","chapterTitle":"Manœuvering"},"sequenceIndex":162},{"id":"artofwar-7-26","text":"In night-fighting, then, make much use of signal-fires and drums, and in fighting by day, of flags and banners, as a means of influencing the ears and eyes of your army.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 7.26","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"7","section":"26","chapterTitle":"Manœuvering"},"sequenceIndex":163},{"id":"artofwar-7-27","text":"A whole army may be robbed of its spirit; a commander-in-chief may be robbed of his presence of mind.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 7.27","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"7","section":"27","chapterTitle":"Manœuvering"},"sequenceIndex":164},{"id":"artofwar-7-28","text":"Now a soldier’s spirit is keenest in the morning; by noonday it has begun to flag; and in the evening, his mind is bent only on returning to camp.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 7.28","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"7","section":"28","chapterTitle":"Manœuvering"},"sequenceIndex":165},{"id":"artofwar-7-29","text":"A clever general, therefore, avoids an army when its spirit is keen, but attacks it when it is sluggish and inclined to return. This is the art of studying moods.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 7.29","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"7","section":"29","chapterTitle":"Manœuvering"},"sequenceIndex":166},{"id":"artofwar-7-30","text":"Disciplined and calm, to await the appearance of disorder and hubbub amongst the enemy:—this is the art of retaining self-possession.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 7.30","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"7","section":"30","chapterTitle":"Manœuvering"},"sequenceIndex":167},{"id":"artofwar-7-31","text":"To be near the goal while the enemy is still far from it, to wait at ease while the enemy is toiling and struggling, to be well-fed while the enemy is famished:—this is the art of husbanding one’s strength.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 7.31","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"7","section":"31","chapterTitle":"Manœuvering"},"sequenceIndex":168},{"id":"artofwar-7-32","text":"To refrain from intercepting an enemy whose banners are in perfect order, to refrain from attacking an army drawn up in calm and confident array:—this is the art of studying circumstances.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 7.32","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"7","section":"32","chapterTitle":"Manœuvering"},"sequenceIndex":169},{"id":"artofwar-7-33","text":"It is a military axiom not to advance uphill against the enemy, nor to oppose him when he comes downhill.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 7.33","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"7","section":"33","chapterTitle":"Manœuvering"},"sequenceIndex":170},{"id":"artofwar-7-34","text":"Do not pursue an enemy who simulates flight; do not attack soldiers whose temper is keen.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 7.34","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"7","section":"34","chapterTitle":"Manœuvering"},"sequenceIndex":171},{"id":"artofwar-7-35","text":"Do not swallow a bait offered by the enemy. Do not interfere with an army that is returning home.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 7.35","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"7","section":"35","chapterTitle":"Manœuvering"},"sequenceIndex":172},{"id":"artofwar-7-36","text":"When you surround an army, leave an outlet free. Do not press a desperate foe too hard.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 7.36","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"7","section":"36","chapterTitle":"Manœuvering"},"sequenceIndex":173},{"id":"artofwar-7-37","text":"Such is the art of warfare.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 7.37","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"7","section":"37","chapterTitle":"Manœuvering"},"sequenceIndex":174},{"id":"artofwar-8-1","text":"Sun Tzŭ said: In war, the general receives his commands from the sovereign, collects his army and concentrates his forces.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 8.1","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"8","section":"1","chapterTitle":"Variation Of Tactics"},"sequenceIndex":175},{"id":"artofwar-8-2","text":"When in difficult country, do not encamp. In country where high roads intersect, join hands with your allies. Do not linger in dangerously isolated positions. In hemmed-in situations, you must resort to stratagem. In a desperate position, you must fight.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 8.2","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"8","section":"2","chapterTitle":"Variation Of Tactics"},"sequenceIndex":176},{"id":"artofwar-8-3","text":"There are roads which must not be followed, armies which must be not attacked, towns which must not be besieged, positions which must not be contested, commands of the sovereign which must not be obeyed.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 8.3","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"8","section":"3","chapterTitle":"Variation Of Tactics"},"sequenceIndex":177},{"id":"artofwar-8-4","text":"The general who thoroughly understands the advantages that accompany variation of tactics knows how to handle his troops.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 8.4","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"8","section":"4","chapterTitle":"Variation Of Tactics"},"sequenceIndex":178},{"id":"artofwar-8-5","text":"The general who does not understand these, may be well acquainted with the configuration of the country, yet he will not be able to turn his knowledge to practical account.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 8.5","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"8","section":"5","chapterTitle":"Variation Of Tactics"},"sequenceIndex":179},{"id":"artofwar-8-6","text":"So, the student of war who is unversed in the art of war of varying his plans, even though he be acquainted with the Five Advantages, will fail to make the best use of his men.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 8.6","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"8","section":"6","chapterTitle":"Variation Of Tactics"},"sequenceIndex":180},{"id":"artofwar-8-7","text":"Hence in the wise leader’s plans, considerations of advantage and of disadvantage will be blended together.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 8.7","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"8","section":"7","chapterTitle":"Variation Of Tactics"},"sequenceIndex":181},{"id":"artofwar-8-8","text":"If our expectation of advantage be tempered in this way, we may succeed in accomplishing the essential part of our schemes.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 8.8","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"8","section":"8","chapterTitle":"Variation Of Tactics"},"sequenceIndex":182},{"id":"artofwar-8-9","text":"If, on the other hand, in the midst of difficulties we are always ready to seize an advantage, we may extricate ourselves from misfortune.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 8.9","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"8","section":"9","chapterTitle":"Variation Of Tactics"},"sequenceIndex":183},{"id":"artofwar-8-10","text":"Reduce the hostile chiefs by inflicting damage on them; and make trouble for them, and keep them constantly engaged; hold out specious allurements, and make them rush to any given point.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 8.10","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"8","section":"10","chapterTitle":"Variation Of Tactics"},"sequenceIndex":184},{"id":"artofwar-8-11","text":"The art of war teaches us to rely not on the likelihood of the enemy’s not coming, but on our own readiness to receive him; not on the chance of his not attacking, but rather on the fact that we have made our position unassailable.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 8.11","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"8","section":"11","chapterTitle":"Variation Of Tactics"},"sequenceIndex":185},{"id":"artofwar-8-12","text":"There are five dangerous faults which may affect a general: (1) Recklessness, which leads to destruction; (2) cowardice, which leads to capture; (3) a hasty temper, which can be provoked by insults; (4) a delicacy of honour which is sensitive to shame; This need not be taken to mean that a sense of honour is really a defect in a general. What Sun Tzŭ condemns is rather an exaggerated sensitiveness to slanderous reports, the thin-skinned man who is stung by opprobrium, however undeserved. Mei Yao-ch’en truly observes, though somewhat paradoxically: \"The seeker after glory should be careless of public opinion.\"] (5) over-solicitude for his men, which exposes him to worry and trouble.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 8.12","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"8","section":"12","chapterTitle":"Variation Of Tactics"},"sequenceIndex":186},{"id":"artofwar-8-13","text":"These are the five besetting sins of a general, ruinous to the conduct of war.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 8.13","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"8","section":"13","chapterTitle":"Variation Of Tactics"},"sequenceIndex":187},{"id":"artofwar-8-14","text":"When an army is overthrown and its leader slain, the cause will surely be found among these five dangerous faults. Let them be a subject of meditation.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 8.14","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"8","section":"14","chapterTitle":"Variation Of Tactics"},"sequenceIndex":188},{"id":"artofwar-9-1","text":"Sun Tzŭ said: We come now to the question of encamping the army, and observing signs of the enemy. Pass quickly over mountains, and keep in the neighbourhood of valleys.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.1","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"1","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":189},{"id":"artofwar-9-2","text":"Camp in high places, facing the sun.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.2","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"2","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":190},{"id":"artofwar-9-4","text":"When an invading force crosses a river in its onward march, do not advance to meet it in mid-stream. It will be best to let half the army get across, and then deliver your attack.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.4","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"4","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":191},{"id":"artofwar-9-5","text":"If you are anxious to fight, you should not go to meet the invader near a river which he has to cross.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.5","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"5","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":192},{"id":"artofwar-9-6","text":"Moor your craft higher up than the enemy, and facing the sun. Do not move up-stream to meet the enemy. So much for river warfare.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.6","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"6","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":193},{"id":"artofwar-9-7","text":"In crossing salt-marshes, your sole concern should be to get over them quickly, without any delay.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.7","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"7","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":194},{"id":"artofwar-9-8","text":"If forced to fight in a salt-marsh, you should have water and grass near you, and get your back to a clump of trees. So much for operations in salt-marshes.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.8","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"8","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":195},{"id":"artofwar-9-9","text":"In dry, level country, take up an easily accessible position with rising ground to your right and on your rear, so that the danger may be in front, and safety lie behind. So much for campaigning in flat country.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.9","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"9","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":196},{"id":"artofwar-9-10","text":"These are the four useful branches of military knowledge which enabled the Yellow Emperor to vanquish four several sovereigns.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.10","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"10","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":197},{"id":"artofwar-9-11","text":"All armies prefer high ground to low, and sunny places to dark.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.11","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"11","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":198},{"id":"artofwar-9-12","text":"If you are careful of your men, and camp on hard ground, the army will be free from disease of every kind, and this will spell victory.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.12","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"12","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":199},{"id":"artofwar-9-13","text":"When you come to a hill or a bank, occupy the sunny side, with the slope on your right rear. Thus you will at once act for the benefit of your soldiers and utilise the natural advantages of the ground.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.13","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"13","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":200},{"id":"artofwar-9-14","text":"When, in consequence of heavy rains up-country, a river which you wish to ford is swollen and flecked with foam, you must wait until it subsides.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.14","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"14","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":201},{"id":"artofwar-9-15","text":"Country in which there are precipitous cliffs with torrents running between, deep natural hollows, The latter defined as \"places enclosed on every side by steep banks, with pools of water at the bottom.\"] confined places, tangled thickets, quagmires and crevasses, should be left with all possible speed and not approached.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.15","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"15","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":202},{"id":"artofwar-9-16","text":"While we keep away from such places, we should get the enemy to approach them; while we face them, we should let the enemy have them on his rear.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.16","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"16","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":203},{"id":"artofwar-9-17","text":"If in the neighbourhood of your camp there should be any hilly country, ponds surrounded by aquatic grass, hollow basins filled with reeds, or woods with thick undergrowth, they must be carefully routed out and searched; for these are places where men in ambush or insidious spies are likely to be lurking.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.17","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"17","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":204},{"id":"artofwar-9-18","text":"When the enemy is close at hand and remains quiet, he is relying on the natural strength of his position.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.18","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"18","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":205},{"id":"artofwar-9-19","text":"When he keeps aloof and tries to provoke a battle, he is anxious for the other side to advance.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.19","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"19","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":206},{"id":"artofwar-9-20","text":"If his place of encampment is easy of access, he is tendering a bait.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.20","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"20","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":207},{"id":"artofwar-9-21","text":"Movement amongst the trees of a forest shows that the enemy is advancing. The appearance of a number of screens in the midst of thick grass means that the enemy wants to make us suspicious.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.21","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"21","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":208},{"id":"artofwar-9-22","text":"The rising of birds in their flight is the sign of an ambuscade. Startled beasts indicate that a sudden attack is coming.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.22","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"22","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":209},{"id":"artofwar-9-23","text":"When there is dust rising in a high column, it is the sign of chariots advancing; when the dust is low, but spread over a wide area, it betokens the approach of infantry. When it branches out in different directions, it shows that parties have been sent to collect firewood. A few clouds of dust moving to and fro signify that the army is encamping.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.23","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"23","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":210},{"id":"artofwar-9-24","text":"Humble words and increased preparations are signs that the enemy is about to advance. Violent language and driving forward as if to the attack are signs that he will retreat.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.24","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"24","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":211},{"id":"artofwar-9-25","text":"When the light chariots come out first and take up a position on the wings, it is a sign that the enemy is forming for battle.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.25","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"25","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":212},{"id":"artofwar-9-26","text":"Peace proposals unaccompanied by a sworn covenant indicate a plot.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.26","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"26","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":213},{"id":"artofwar-9-27","text":"When there is much running about and the soldiers fall into rank, it means that the critical moment has come.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.27","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"27","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":214},{"id":"artofwar-9-28","text":"When some are seen advancing and some retreating, it is a lure.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.28","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"28","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":215},{"id":"artofwar-9-29","text":"When the soldiers stand leaning on their spears, they are faint from want of food.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.29","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"29","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":216},{"id":"artofwar-9-30","text":"If those who are sent to draw water begin by drinking themselves, the army is suffering from thirst.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.30","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"30","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":217},{"id":"artofwar-9-31","text":"If the enemy sees an advantage to be gained and makes no effort to secure it, the soldiers are exhausted.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.31","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"31","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":218},{"id":"artofwar-9-32","text":"If birds gather on any spot, it is unoccupied. Clamour by night betokens nervousness.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.32","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"32","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":219},{"id":"artofwar-9-33","text":"If there is disturbance in the camp, the general’s authority is weak. If the banners and flags are shifted about, sedition is afoot. If the officers are angry, it means that the men are weary.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.33","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"33","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":220},{"id":"artofwar-9-34","text":"When an army feeds its horses with grain and kills its cattle for food, and when the men do not hang their cooking-pots over the camp-fires, showing that they will not return to their tents, you may know that they are determined to fight to the death.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.34","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"34","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":221},{"id":"artofwar-9-35","text":"The sight of men whispering together in small knots or speaking in subdued tones points to disaffection amongst the rank and file.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.35","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"35","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":222},{"id":"artofwar-9-36","text":"Too frequent rewards signify that the enemy is at the end of his resources; too many punishments betray a condition of dire distress.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.36","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"36","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":223},{"id":"artofwar-9-37","text":"To begin by bluster, but afterwards to take fright at the enemy’s numbers, shows a supreme lack of intelligence.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.37","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"37","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":224},{"id":"artofwar-9-38","text":"When envoys are sent with compliments in their mouths, it is a sign that the enemy wishes for a truce.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.38","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"38","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":225},{"id":"artofwar-9-39","text":"If the enemy’s troops march up angrily and remain facing ours for a long time without either joining battle or taking themselves off again, the situation is one that demands great vigilance and circumspection.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.39","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"39","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":226},{"id":"artofwar-9-40","text":"If our troops are no more in number than the enemy, that is amply sufficient; it only means that no direct attack can be made. What we can do is simply to concentrate all our available strength, keep a close watch on the enemy, and obtain reinforcements.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.40","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"40","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":227},{"id":"artofwar-9-41","text":"He who exercises no forethought but makes light of his opponents is sure to be captured by them.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.41","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"41","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":228},{"id":"artofwar-9-42","text":"If soldiers are punished before they have grown attached to you, they will not prove submissive; and, unless submissive, then will be practically useless. If, when the soldiers have become attached to you, punishments are not enforced, they will still be useless.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.42","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"42","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":229},{"id":"artofwar-9-43","text":"Therefore soldiers must be treated in the first instance with humanity, but kept under control by means of iron discipline. This is a certain road to victory.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.43","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"43","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":230},{"id":"artofwar-9-44","text":"If in training soldiers commands are habitually enforced, the army will be well-disciplined; if not, its discipline will be bad.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.44","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"44","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":231},{"id":"artofwar-9-45","text":"If a general shows confidence in his men but always insists on his orders being obeyed, the gain will be mutual.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 9.45","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"9","section":"45","chapterTitle":"The Army On The March"},"sequenceIndex":232},{"id":"artofwar-10-1","text":"Sun Tzŭ said: We may distinguish six kinds of terrain, to wit: (1) Accessible ground; (2) entangling ground; (3) temporising ground; (4) narrow passes; (5) precipitous heights; (6) positions at a great distance from the enemy.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 10.1","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"10","section":"1","chapterTitle":"Terrain"},"sequenceIndex":233},{"id":"artofwar-10-2","text":"Ground which can be freely traversed by both sides is called _accessible_.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 10.2","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"10","section":"2","chapterTitle":"Terrain"},"sequenceIndex":234},{"id":"artofwar-10-3","text":"With regard to ground of this nature, be before the enemy in occupying the raised and sunny spots, and carefully guard your line of supplies. we could wish that Sun Tzŭ had done more than skirt the edge of this important subject here and in I. § 10, VII. § 11. Col. Henderson says: \"The line of supply may be said to be as vital to the existence of an army as the heart to the life of a human being. Just as the duelist who finds his adversary’s point menacing him with certain death, and his own guard astray, is compelled to conform to his adversary’s movements, and to content himself with warding off his thrusts, so the commander whose communications are suddenly threatened finds himself in a false position, and he will be fortunate if he has not to change all his plans, to split up his force into more or less isolated detachments, and to fight with inferior numbers on ground which he has not had time to prepare, and where defeat will not be an ordinary failure, but will entail the ruin or surrender of his whole army.\" [2] Then you will be able to fight with advantage.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 10.3","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"10","section":"3","chapterTitle":"Terrain"},"sequenceIndex":235},{"id":"artofwar-10-4","text":"Ground which can be abandoned but is hard to re-occupy is called _entangling_.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 10.4","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"10","section":"4","chapterTitle":"Terrain"},"sequenceIndex":236},{"id":"artofwar-10-5","text":"From a position of this sort, if the enemy is unprepared, you may sally forth and defeat him. But if the enemy is prepared for your coming, and you fail to defeat him, then, return being impossible, disaster will ensue.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 10.5","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"10","section":"5","chapterTitle":"Terrain"},"sequenceIndex":237},{"id":"artofwar-10-6","text":"When the position is such that neither side will gain by making the first move, it is called _temporising_ ground.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 10.6","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"10","section":"6","chapterTitle":"Terrain"},"sequenceIndex":238},{"id":"artofwar-10-7","text":"In a position of this sort, even though the enemy should offer us an attractive bait, it will be advisable not to stir forth, but rather to retreat, thus enticing the enemy in his turn; then, when part of his army has come out, we may deliver our attack with advantage.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 10.7","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"10","section":"7","chapterTitle":"Terrain"},"sequenceIndex":239},{"id":"artofwar-10-8","text":"With regard to _narrow passes_, if you can occupy them first, let them be strongly garrisoned and await the advent of the enemy.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 10.8","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"10","section":"8","chapterTitle":"Terrain"},"sequenceIndex":240},{"id":"artofwar-10-9","text":"Should the enemy forestall you in occupying a pass, do not go after him if the pass is fully garrisoned, but only if it is weakly garrisoned.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 10.9","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"10","section":"9","chapterTitle":"Terrain"},"sequenceIndex":241},{"id":"artofwar-10-10","text":"With regard to _precipitous heights_, if you are beforehand with your adversary, you should occupy the raised and sunny spots, and there wait for him to come up.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 10.10","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"10","section":"10","chapterTitle":"Terrain"},"sequenceIndex":242},{"id":"artofwar-10-11","text":"If the enemy has occupied them before you, do not follow him, but retreat and try to entice him away.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 10.11","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"10","section":"11","chapterTitle":"Terrain"},"sequenceIndex":243},{"id":"artofwar-10-12","text":"If you are situated at a great distance from the enemy, and the strength of the two armies is equal, it is not easy to provoke a battle, and fighting will be to your disadvantage.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 10.12","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"10","section":"12","chapterTitle":"Terrain"},"sequenceIndex":244},{"id":"artofwar-10-13","text":"These six are the principles connected with Earth. The general who has attained a responsible post must be careful to study them.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 10.13","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"10","section":"13","chapterTitle":"Terrain"},"sequenceIndex":245},{"id":"artofwar-10-14","text":"Now an army is exposed to six several calamities, not arising from natural causes, but from faults for which the general is responsible. These are: (1) Flight; (2) insubordination; (3) collapse; (4) ruin; (5) disorganisation; (6) rout.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 10.14","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"10","section":"14","chapterTitle":"Terrain"},"sequenceIndex":246},{"id":"artofwar-10-15","text":"Other conditions being equal, if one force is hurled against another ten times its size, the result will be the _flight_ of the former.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 10.15","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"10","section":"15","chapterTitle":"Terrain"},"sequenceIndex":247},{"id":"artofwar-10-16","text":"When the common soldiers are too strong and their officers too weak, the result is _insubordination_. When the officers are too strong and the common soldiers too weak, the result is _collapse_.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 10.16","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"10","section":"16","chapterTitle":"Terrain"},"sequenceIndex":248},{"id":"artofwar-10-17","text":"When the higher officers are angry and insubordinate, and on meeting the enemy give battle on their own account from a feeling of resentment, before the commander-in-chief can tell whether or no he is in a position to fight, the result is _ruin_.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 10.17","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"10","section":"17","chapterTitle":"Terrain"},"sequenceIndex":249},{"id":"artofwar-10-18","text":"When the general is weak and without authority; when his orders are not clear and distinct; when there are no fixed duties assigned to officers and men, and the ranks are formed in a slovenly haphazard manner, the result is utter _disorganisation_.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 10.18","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"10","section":"18","chapterTitle":"Terrain"},"sequenceIndex":250},{"id":"artofwar-10-19","text":"When a general, unable to estimate the enemy’s strength, allows an inferior force to engage a larger one, or hurls a weak detachment against a powerful one, and neglects to place picked soldiers in the front rank, the result must be a _rout_.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 10.19","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"10","section":"19","chapterTitle":"Terrain"},"sequenceIndex":251},{"id":"artofwar-10-20","text":"These are six ways of courting defeat, which must be carefully noted by the general who has attained a responsible post.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 10.20","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"10","section":"20","chapterTitle":"Terrain"},"sequenceIndex":252},{"id":"artofwar-10-21","text":"The natural formation of the country is the soldier’s best ally; but a power of estimating the adversary, of controlling the forces of victory, and of shrewdly calculating difficulties, dangers and distances, constitutes the test of a great general.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 10.21","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"10","section":"21","chapterTitle":"Terrain"},"sequenceIndex":253},{"id":"artofwar-10-22","text":"He who knows these things, and in fighting puts his knowledge into practice, will win his battles. He who knows them not, nor practises them, will surely be defeated.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 10.22","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"10","section":"22","chapterTitle":"Terrain"},"sequenceIndex":254},{"id":"artofwar-10-23","text":"If fighting is sure to result in victory, then you must fight, even though the ruler forbid it; if fighting will not result in victory, then you must not fight even at the ruler’s bidding.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 10.23","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"10","section":"23","chapterTitle":"Terrain"},"sequenceIndex":255},{"id":"artofwar-10-24","text":"The general who advances without coveting fame and retreats without fearing disgrace, whose only thought is to protect his country and do good service for his sovereign, is the jewel of the kingdom.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 10.24","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"10","section":"24","chapterTitle":"Terrain"},"sequenceIndex":256},{"id":"artofwar-10-25","text":"Regard your soldiers as your children, and they will follow you into the deepest valleys; look on them as your own beloved sons, and they will stand by you even unto death.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 10.25","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"10","section":"25","chapterTitle":"Terrain"},"sequenceIndex":257},{"id":"artofwar-10-26","text":"If, however, you are indulgent, but unable to make your authority felt; kind-hearted, but unable to enforce your commands; and incapable, moreover, of quelling disorder: then your soldiers must be likened to spoilt children; they are useless for any practical purpose.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 10.26","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"10","section":"26","chapterTitle":"Terrain"},"sequenceIndex":258},{"id":"artofwar-10-27","text":"If we know that our own men are in a condition to attack, but are unaware that the enemy is not open to attack, we have gone only halfway towards victory.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 10.27","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"10","section":"27","chapterTitle":"Terrain"},"sequenceIndex":259},{"id":"artofwar-10-28","text":"If we know that the enemy is open to attack, but are unaware that our own men are not in a condition to attack, we have gone only halfway towards victory.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 10.28","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"10","section":"28","chapterTitle":"Terrain"},"sequenceIndex":260},{"id":"artofwar-10-29","text":"If we know that the enemy is open to attack, and also know that our men are in a condition to attack, but are unaware that the nature of the ground makes fighting impracticable, we have still gone only halfway towards victory.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 10.29","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"10","section":"29","chapterTitle":"Terrain"},"sequenceIndex":261},{"id":"artofwar-10-30","text":"Hence the experienced soldier, once in motion, is never bewildered; once he has broken camp, he is never at a loss.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 10.30","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"10","section":"30","chapterTitle":"Terrain"},"sequenceIndex":262},{"id":"artofwar-10-31","text":"Hence the saying: If you know the enemy and know yourself, your victory will not stand in doubt; if you know Heaven and know Earth, you may make your victory complete.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 10.31","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"10","section":"31","chapterTitle":"Terrain"},"sequenceIndex":263},{"id":"artofwar-11-1","text":"Sun Tzŭ said: The art of war recognises nine varieties of ground: (1) Dispersive ground; (2) facile ground; (3) contentious ground; (4) open ground; (5) ground of intersecting highways; (6) serious ground; (7) difficult ground; (8) hemmed-in ground; (9) desperate ground.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.1","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"1","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":264},{"id":"artofwar-11-2","text":"When a chieftain is fighting in his own territory, it is dispersive ground.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.2","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"2","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":265},{"id":"artofwar-11-3","text":"When he has penetrated into hostile territory, but to no great distance, it is facile ground.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.3","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"3","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":266},{"id":"artofwar-11-4","text":"Ground the possession of which imports great advantage to either side, is contentious ground.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.4","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"4","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":267},{"id":"artofwar-11-5","text":"Ground on which each side has liberty of movement is open ground.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.5","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"5","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":268},{"id":"artofwar-11-6","text":"Ground which forms the key to three contiguous states, so that he who occupies it first has most of the Empire at his command, is ground of intersecting highways.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.6","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"6","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":269},{"id":"artofwar-11-7","text":"When an army has penetrated into the heart of a hostile country, leaving a number of fortified cities in its rear, it is serious ground.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.7","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"7","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":270},{"id":"artofwar-11-8","text":"Mountain forests, rugged steeps, marshes and fens—all country that is hard to traverse: this is difficult ground.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.8","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"8","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":271},{"id":"artofwar-11-9","text":"Ground which is reached through narrow gorges, and from which we can only retire by tortuous paths, so that a small number of the enemy would suffice to crush a large body of our men: this is hemmed in ground.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.9","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"9","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":272},{"id":"artofwar-11-10","text":"Ground on which we can only be saved from destruction by fighting without delay, is desperate ground.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.10","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"10","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":273},{"id":"artofwar-11-11","text":"On dispersive ground, therefore, fight not. On facile ground, halt not. On contentious ground, attack not.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.11","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"11","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":274},{"id":"artofwar-11-12","text":"On open ground, do not try to block the enemy’s way. On ground of intersecting highways, join hands with your allies.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.12","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"12","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":275},{"id":"artofwar-11-13","text":"On serious ground, gather in plunder. In difficult ground, keep steadily on the march.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.13","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"13","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":276},{"id":"artofwar-11-14","text":"On hemmed-in ground, resort to stratagem. On desperate ground, fight.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.14","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"14","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":277},{"id":"artofwar-11-15","text":"Those who were called skilful leaders of old knew how to drive a wedge between the enemy’s front and rear; to prevent co-operation between his large and small divisions; to hinder the good troops from rescuing the bad, the officers from rallying their men.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.15","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"15","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":278},{"id":"artofwar-11-16","text":"When the enemy’s men were scattered, they prevented them from concentrating; even when their forces were united, they managed to keep them in disorder.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.16","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"16","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":279},{"id":"artofwar-11-17","text":"When it was to their advantage, they made a forward move; when otherwise, they stopped still.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.17","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"17","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":280},{"id":"artofwar-11-18","text":"If asked how to cope with a great host of the enemy in orderly array and on the point of marching to the attack, I should say: \"Begin by seizing something which your opponent holds dear; then he will be amenable to your will.\"","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.18","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"18","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":281},{"id":"artofwar-11-19","text":"Rapidity is the essence of war: take advantage of the enemy’s unreadiness, make your way by unexpected routes, and attack unguarded spots.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.19","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"19","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":282},{"id":"artofwar-11-20","text":"The following are the principles to be observed by an invading force: The further you penetrate into a country, the greater will be the solidarity of your troops, and thus the defenders will not prevail against you.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.20","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"20","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":283},{"id":"artofwar-11-21","text":"Make forays in fertile country in order to supply your army with food.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.21","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"21","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":284},{"id":"artofwar-11-22","text":"Carefully study the well-being of your men, and do not overtax them. Concentrate your energy and hoard your strength. Keep your army continually on the move, and devise unfathomable plans.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.22","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"22","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":285},{"id":"artofwar-11-23","text":"Throw your soldiers into positions whence there is no escape, and they will prefer death to flight. If they will face death, there is nothing they may not achieve. Officers and men alike will put forth their uttermost strength.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.23","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"23","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":286},{"id":"artofwar-11-24","text":"Soldiers when in desperate straits lose the sense of fear. If there is no place of refuge, they will stand firm. If they are in the heart of a hostile country, they will show a stubborn front. If there is no help for it, they will fight hard.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.24","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"24","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":287},{"id":"artofwar-11-25","text":"Thus, without waiting to be marshalled, the soldiers will be constantly on the _qui vive;_ without waiting to be asked, they will do your will; without restrictions, they will be faithful; without giving orders, they can be trusted.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.25","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"25","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":288},{"id":"artofwar-11-26","text":"Prohibit the taking of omens, and do away with superstitious doubts. Then, until death itself comes, no calamity need be feared.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.26","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"26","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":289},{"id":"artofwar-11-27","text":"If our soldiers are not overburdened with money, it is not because they have a distaste for riches; if their lives are not unduly long, it is not because they are disinclined to longevity.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.27","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"27","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":290},{"id":"artofwar-11-28","text":"On the day they are ordered out to battle, your soldiers may weep, those sitting up bedewing their garments, and those lying down letting the tears run down their cheeks. But let them once be brought to bay, and they will display the courage of a Chu or a Kuei.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.28","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"28","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":291},{"id":"artofwar-11-29","text":"The skilful tactician may be likened to the _shuai-jan_. Now the _shuai-jan_ is a snake that is found in the Ch‘ang mountains. Strike at its head, and you will be attacked by its tail; strike at its tail, and you will be attacked by its head; strike at its middle, and you will be attacked by head and tail both.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.29","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"29","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":292},{"id":"artofwar-11-30","text":"Asked if an army can be made to imitate the _shuai-jan_, I should answer, Yes. For the men of Wu and the men of Yüeh are enemies; yet if they are crossing a river in the same boat and are caught by a storm, they will come to each other’s assistance just as the left hand helps the right.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.30","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"30","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":293},{"id":"artofwar-11-31","text":"Hence it is not enough to put one’s trust in the tethering of horses, and the burying of chariot wheels in the ground.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.31","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"31","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":294},{"id":"artofwar-11-32","text":"The principle on which to manage an army is to set up one standard of courage which all must reach. one.\" If the ideal army is to form a single organic whole, then it follows that the resolution and spirit of its component parts must be of the same quality, or at any rate must not fall below a certain standard. Wellington’s seemingly ungrateful description of his army at Waterloo as \"the worst he had ever commanded\" meant no more than that it was deficient in this important particular—unity of spirit and courage. Had he not foreseen the Belgian defections and carefully kept those troops in the background, he would almost certainly have lost the day.]","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.32","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"32","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":295},{"id":"artofwar-11-33","text":"How to make the best of both strong and weak—that is a question involving the proper use of ground.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.33","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"33","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":296},{"id":"artofwar-11-34","text":"Thus the skilful general conducts his army just as though he were leading a single man, willy-nilly, by the hand.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.34","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"34","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":297},{"id":"artofwar-11-35","text":"It is the business of a general to be quiet and thus ensure secrecy; upright and just, and thus maintain order.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.35","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"35","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":298},{"id":"artofwar-11-36","text":"He must be able to mystify his officers and men by false reports and appearances, and thus keep them in total ignorance.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.36","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"36","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":299},{"id":"artofwar-11-37","text":"By altering his arrangements and changing his plans, he keeps the enemy without definite knowledge. By shifting his camp and taking circuitous routes, he prevents the enemy from anticipating his purpose.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.37","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"37","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":300},{"id":"artofwar-11-38","text":"At the critical moment, the leader of an army acts like one who has climbed up a height and then kicks away the ladder behind him. He carries his men deep into hostile territory before he shows his hand.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.38","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"38","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":301},{"id":"artofwar-11-39","text":"He burns his boats and breaks his cooking-pots; like a shepherd driving a flock of sheep, he drives his men this way and that, and none knows whither he is going.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.39","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"39","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":302},{"id":"artofwar-11-40","text":"To muster his host and bring it into danger:—this may be termed the business of the general.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.40","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"40","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":303},{"id":"artofwar-11-41","text":"The different measures suited to the nine varieties of ground; the expediency of aggressive or defensive tactics; and the fundamental laws of human nature: these are things that must most certainly be studied.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.41","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"41","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":304},{"id":"artofwar-11-42","text":"When invading hostile territory, the general principle is, that penetrating deeply brings cohesion; penetrating but a short way means dispersion.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.42","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"42","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":305},{"id":"artofwar-11-43","text":"When you leave your own country behind, and take your army across neighbourhood territory, you find yourself on critical ground. When there are means of communication on all four sides, the ground is one of intersecting highways.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.43","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"43","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":306},{"id":"artofwar-11-44","text":"When you penetrate deeply into a country, it is serious ground. When you penetrate but a little way, it is facile ground.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.44","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"44","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":307},{"id":"artofwar-11-45","text":"When you have the enemy’s strongholds on your rear, and narrow passes in front, it is hemmed-in ground. When there is no place of refuge at all, it is desperate ground.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.45","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"45","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":308},{"id":"artofwar-11-46","text":"Therefore, on dispersive ground, I would inspire my men with unity of purpose. On facile ground, I would see that there is close connection between all parts of my army.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.46","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"46","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":309},{"id":"artofwar-11-47","text":"On contentious ground, I would hurry up my rear.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.47","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"47","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":310},{"id":"artofwar-11-48","text":"On open ground, I would keep a vigilant eye on my defences. On ground of intersecting highways, I would consolidate my alliances.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.48","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"48","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":311},{"id":"artofwar-11-49","text":"On serious ground, I would try to ensure a continuous stream of supplies. On difficult ground, I would keep pushing on along the road.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.49","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"49","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":312},{"id":"artofwar-11-50","text":"On hemmed-in ground, I would block any way of retreat. On desperate ground, I would proclaim to my soldiers the hopelessness of saving their lives. Tu Yu says: \"Burn your baggage and impedimenta, throw away your stores and provisions, choke up the wells, destroy your cooking-stoves, and make it plain to your men that they cannot survive, but must fight to the death.\" Mei Yao-ch’en says: \"The only chance of life lies in giving up all hope of it.\" This concludes what Sun Tzŭ has to say about \"grounds\" and the \"variations\" corresponding to them. Reviewing the passages which bear on this important subject, we cannot fail to be struck by the desultory and unmethodical fashion in which it is treated. Sun Tzŭ begins abruptly in VIII. § 2 to enumerate \"variations\" before touching on \"grounds\" at all, but only mentions five, namely nos. 7, 5, 8 and 9 of the subsequent list, and one that is not included in it. A few varieties of ground are dealt with in the earlier portion of chap. IX, and then chap. X sets forth six new grounds, with six variations of plan to match. None of these is mentioned again, though the first is hardly to be distinguished from ground no. 4 in the next chapter. At last, in chap. XI, we come to the Nine Grounds par excellence, immediately followed by the variations. This takes us down to § 14. In §§ 43-45, fresh definitions are provided for nos. 5, 6, 2, 8 and 9 (in the order given), as well as for the tenth ground noticed in chap. VIII; and finally, the nine variations are enumerated once more from beginning to end, all, with the exception of 5, 6 and 7, being different from those previously given. Though it is impossible to account for the present state of Sun Tzŭ’s text, a few suggestive facts maybe brought into prominence: (1) Chap. VIII, according to the title, should deal with nine variations, whereas only five appear. (2) It is an abnormally short chapter. (3) Chap. XI is entitled The Nine Grounds. Several of these are defined twice over, besides which there are two distinct lists of the corresponding variations. (4) The length of the chapter is disproportionate, being double that of any other except IX. I do not propose to draw any inferences from these facts, beyond the general conclusion that Sun Tzŭ’s work cannot have come down to us in the shape in which it left his hands: chap. VIII is obviously defective and probably out of place, while XI seems to contain matter that has either been added by a later hand or ought to appear elsewhere.]","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.50","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"50","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":313},{"id":"artofwar-11-51","text":"For it is the soldier’s disposition to offer an obstinate resistance when surrounded, to fight hard when he cannot help himself, and to obey promptly when he has fallen into danger.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.51","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"51","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":314},{"id":"artofwar-11-52","text":"We cannot enter into alliance with neighbouring princes until we are acquainted with their designs. We are not fit to lead an army on the march unless we are familiar with the face of the country—its mountains and forests, its pitfalls and precipices, its marshes and swamps. We shall be unable to turn natural advantages to account unless we make use of local guides.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.52","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"52","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":315},{"id":"artofwar-11-53","text":"To be ignorant of any one of the following four or five principles does not befit a warlike prince.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.53","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"53","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":316},{"id":"artofwar-11-54","text":"When a warlike prince attacks a powerful state, his generalship shows itself in preventing the concentration of the enemy’s forces. He overawes his opponents, and their allies are prevented from joining against him.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.54","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"54","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":317},{"id":"artofwar-11-55","text":"Hence he does not strive to ally himself with all and sundry, nor does he foster the power of other states. He carries out his own secret designs, keeping his antagonists in awe. Thus he is able to capture their cities and overthrow their kingdoms.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.55","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"55","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":318},{"id":"artofwar-11-56","text":"Bestow rewards without regard to rule, issue orders without regard to previous arrangements; and you will be able to handle a whole army as though you had to do with but a single man.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.56","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"56","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":319},{"id":"artofwar-11-57","text":"Confront your soldiers with the deed itself; never let them know your design. When the outlook is bright, bring it before their eyes; but tell them nothing when the situation is gloomy.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.57","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"57","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":320},{"id":"artofwar-11-58","text":"Place your army in deadly peril, and it will survive; plunge it into desperate straits, and it will come off in safety.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.58","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"58","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":321},{"id":"artofwar-11-59","text":"For it is precisely when a force has fallen into harm’s way that is capable of striking a blow for victory.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.59","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"59","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":322},{"id":"artofwar-11-60","text":"Success in warfare is gained by carefully accommodating ourselves to the enemy’s purpose.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.60","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"60","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":323},{"id":"artofwar-11-61","text":"By persistently hanging on the enemy’s flank, we shall succeed in the long run in killing the commander-in-chief.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.61","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"61","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":324},{"id":"artofwar-11-62","text":"This is called ability to accomplish a thing by sheer cunning.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.62","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"62","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":325},{"id":"artofwar-11-63","text":"On the day that you take up your command, block the frontier passes, destroy the official tallies, and stop the passage of all emissaries.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.63","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"63","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":326},{"id":"artofwar-11-64","text":"Be stern in the council-chamber, so that you may control the situation.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.64","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"64","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":327},{"id":"artofwar-11-65","text":"If the enemy leaves a door open, you must rush in.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.65","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"65","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":328},{"id":"artofwar-11-66","text":"Forestall your opponent by seizing what he holds dear, and subtly contrive to time his arrival on the ground.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.66","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"66","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":329},{"id":"artofwar-11-67","text":"Walk in the path defined by rule, and accommodate yourself to the enemy until you can fight a decisive battle.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.67","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"67","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":330},{"id":"artofwar-11-68","text":"At first, then, exhibit the coyness of a maiden, until the enemy gives you an opening; afterwards emulate the rapidity of a running hare, and it will be too late for the enemy to oppose you.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 11.68","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"11","section":"68","chapterTitle":"The Nine Situations"},"sequenceIndex":331},{"id":"artofwar-12-1","text":"Sun Tzŭ said: There are five ways of attacking with fire. The first is to burn soldiers in their camp; the second is to burn stores; the third is to burn baggage-trains; the fourth is to burn arsenals and magazines; the fifth is to hurl dropping fire amongst the enemy.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 12.1","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"12","section":"1","chapterTitle":"The Attack By Fire"},"sequenceIndex":332},{"id":"artofwar-12-2","text":"In order to carry out an attack, we must have means available. the material for raising fire should always be kept in readiness.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 12.2","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"12","section":"2","chapterTitle":"The Attack By Fire"},"sequenceIndex":333},{"id":"artofwar-12-3","text":"There is a proper season for making attacks with fire, and special days for starting a conflagration.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 12.3","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"12","section":"3","chapterTitle":"The Attack By Fire"},"sequenceIndex":334},{"id":"artofwar-12-4","text":"The proper season is when the weather is very dry; the special days are those when the moon is in the constellations of the Sieve, the Wall, the Wing or the Cross-bar; for these four are all days of rising wind.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 12.4","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"12","section":"4","chapterTitle":"The Attack By Fire"},"sequenceIndex":335},{"id":"artofwar-12-5","text":"In attacking with fire, one should be prepared to meet five possible developments:","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 12.5","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"12","section":"5","chapterTitle":"The Attack By Fire"},"sequenceIndex":336},{"id":"artofwar-12-6","text":"(1) When fire breaks out inside the enemy’s camp, respond at once with an attack from without.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 12.6","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"12","section":"6","chapterTitle":"The Attack By Fire"},"sequenceIndex":337},{"id":"artofwar-12-7","text":"(2) If there is an outbreak of fire, but the enemy’s soldiers remain quiet, bide your time and do not attack.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 12.7","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"12","section":"7","chapterTitle":"The Attack By Fire"},"sequenceIndex":338},{"id":"artofwar-12-8","text":"(3) When the force of the flames has reached its height, follow it up with an attack, if that is practicable; if not, stay where you are.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 12.8","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"12","section":"8","chapterTitle":"The Attack By Fire"},"sequenceIndex":339},{"id":"artofwar-12-9","text":"(4) If it is possible to make an assault with fire from without, do not wait for it to break out within, but deliver your attack at a favourable moment. ] ] ] ] ]","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 12.9","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"12","section":"9","chapterTitle":"The Attack By Fire"},"sequenceIndex":340},{"id":"artofwar-12-10","text":"(5) When you start a fire, be to windward of it. Do not attack from the leeward.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 12.10","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"12","section":"10","chapterTitle":"The Attack By Fire"},"sequenceIndex":341},{"id":"artofwar-12-11","text":"A wind that rises in the daytime lasts long, but a night breeze soon falls.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 12.11","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"12","section":"11","chapterTitle":"The Attack By Fire"},"sequenceIndex":342},{"id":"artofwar-12-12","text":"In every army, the five developments connected with fire must be known, the movements of the stars calculated, and a watch kept for the proper days.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 12.12","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"12","section":"12","chapterTitle":"The Attack By Fire"},"sequenceIndex":343},{"id":"artofwar-12-13","text":"Hence those who use fire as an aid to the attack show intelligence; those who use water as an aid to the attack gain an accession of strength.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 12.13","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"12","section":"13","chapterTitle":"The Attack By Fire"},"sequenceIndex":344},{"id":"artofwar-12-14","text":"By means of water, an enemy may be intercepted, but not robbed of all his belongings.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 12.14","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"12","section":"14","chapterTitle":"The Attack By Fire"},"sequenceIndex":345},{"id":"artofwar-12-15","text":"Unhappy is the fate of one who tries to win his battles and succeed in his attacks without cultivating the spirit of enterprise; for the result is waste of time and general stagnation.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 12.15","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"12","section":"15","chapterTitle":"The Attack By Fire"},"sequenceIndex":346},{"id":"artofwar-12-16","text":"Hence the saying: The enlightened ruler lays his plans well ahead; the good general cultivates his resources.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 12.16","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"12","section":"16","chapterTitle":"The Attack By Fire"},"sequenceIndex":347},{"id":"artofwar-12-17","text":"Move not unless you see an advantage; use not your troops unless there is something to be gained; fight not unless the position is critical.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 12.17","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"12","section":"17","chapterTitle":"The Attack By Fire"},"sequenceIndex":348},{"id":"artofwar-12-18","text":"No ruler should put troops into the field merely to gratify his own spleen; no general should fight a battle simply out of pique.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 12.18","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"12","section":"18","chapterTitle":"The Attack By Fire"},"sequenceIndex":349},{"id":"artofwar-12-19","text":"If it is to your advantage, make a forward move; if not, stay where you are.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 12.19","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"12","section":"19","chapterTitle":"The Attack By Fire"},"sequenceIndex":350},{"id":"artofwar-12-20","text":"Anger may in time change to gladness; vexation may be succeeded by content.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 12.20","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"12","section":"20","chapterTitle":"The Attack By Fire"},"sequenceIndex":351},{"id":"artofwar-12-21","text":"But a kingdom that has once been destroyed can never come again into being; nor can the dead ever be brought back to life.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 12.21","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"12","section":"21","chapterTitle":"The Attack By Fire"},"sequenceIndex":352},{"id":"artofwar-12-22","text":"Hence the enlightened ruler is heedful, and the good general full of caution. This is the way to keep a country at peace and an army intact.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 12.22","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"12","section":"22","chapterTitle":"The Attack By Fire"},"sequenceIndex":353},{"id":"artofwar-13-1","text":"Sun Tzŭ said: Raising a host of a hundred thousand men and marching them great distances entails heavy loss on the people and a drain on the resources of the State. The daily expenditure will amount to a thousand ounces of silver. There will be commotion at home and abroad, and men will drop down exhausted on the highways. As many as seven hundred thousand families will be impeded in their labor.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 13.1","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"13","section":"1","chapterTitle":"The Use Of Spies"},"sequenceIndex":354},{"id":"artofwar-13-2","text":"Hostile armies may face each other for years, striving for the victory which is decided in a single day. This being so, to remain in ignorance of the enemy’s condition simply because one grudges the outlay of a hundred ounces of silver in honours and emoluments, is the height of inhumanity.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 13.2","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"13","section":"2","chapterTitle":"The Use Of Spies"},"sequenceIndex":355},{"id":"artofwar-13-3","text":"One who acts thus is no leader of men, no present help to his sovereign, no master of victory.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 13.3","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"13","section":"3","chapterTitle":"The Use Of Spies"},"sequenceIndex":356},{"id":"artofwar-13-4","text":"Thus, what enables the wise sovereign and the good general to strike and conquer, and achieve things beyond the reach of ordinary men, is _foreknowledge_.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 13.4","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"13","section":"4","chapterTitle":"The Use Of Spies"},"sequenceIndex":357},{"id":"artofwar-13-5","text":"Now this foreknowledge cannot be elicited from spirits; it cannot be obtained inductively from experience, nor by any deductive calculation.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 13.5","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"13","section":"5","chapterTitle":"The Use Of Spies"},"sequenceIndex":358},{"id":"artofwar-13-6","text":"Knowledge of the enemy’s dispositions can only be obtained from other men.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 13.6","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"13","section":"6","chapterTitle":"The Use Of Spies"},"sequenceIndex":359},{"id":"artofwar-13-7","text":"Hence the use of spies, of whom there are five classes: (1) Local spies; (2) inward spies; (3) converted spies; (4) doomed spies; (5) surviving spies.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 13.7","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"13","section":"7","chapterTitle":"The Use Of Spies"},"sequenceIndex":360},{"id":"artofwar-13-8","text":"When these five kinds of spy are all at work, none can discover the secret system. This is called \"divine manipulation of the threads.\" It is the sovereign’s most precious faculty.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 13.8","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"13","section":"8","chapterTitle":"The Use Of Spies"},"sequenceIndex":361},{"id":"artofwar-13-9","text":"Having _local spies_ means employing the services of the inhabitants of a district.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 13.9","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"13","section":"9","chapterTitle":"The Use Of Spies"},"sequenceIndex":362},{"id":"artofwar-13-10","text":"Having _inward spies_, making use of officials of the enemy.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 13.10","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"13","section":"10","chapterTitle":"The Use Of Spies"},"sequenceIndex":363},{"id":"artofwar-13-11","text":"Having _converted spies_, getting hold of the enemy’s spies and using them for our own purposes.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 13.11","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"13","section":"11","chapterTitle":"The Use Of Spies"},"sequenceIndex":364},{"id":"artofwar-13-12","text":"Having _doomed spies_, doing certain things openly for purposes of deception, and allowing our own spies to know of them and report them to the enemy.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 13.12","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"13","section":"12","chapterTitle":"The Use Of Spies"},"sequenceIndex":365},{"id":"artofwar-13-13","text":"_Surviving spies_, finally, are those who bring back news from the enemy’s camp. sent Ta-hsi Wu to spy upon the enemy. He was accompanied by two other men. All three were on horseback and wore the enemy’s uniform. When it was dark, they dismounted a few hundred feet away from the enemy’s camp and stealthily crept up to listen, until they succeeded in catching the passwords used in the army. Then they got on their horses again and boldly passed through the camp under the guise of night-watchmen; and more than once, happening to come across a soldier who was committing some breach of discipline, they actually stopped to give the culprit a sound cudgeling! Thus they managed to return with the fullest possible information about the enemy’s dispositions, and received warm commendation from the Emperor, who in consequence of their report was able to inflict a severe defeat on his adversary.\"]","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 13.13","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"13","section":"13","chapterTitle":"The Use Of Spies"},"sequenceIndex":366},{"id":"artofwar-13-14","text":"Hence it is that with none in the whole army are more intimate relations to be maintained than with spies. None should be more liberally rewarded. In no other business should greater secrecy be preserved.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 13.14","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"13","section":"14","chapterTitle":"The Use Of Spies"},"sequenceIndex":367},{"id":"artofwar-13-15","text":"Spies cannot be usefully employed without a certain intuitive sagacity.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 13.15","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"13","section":"15","chapterTitle":"The Use Of Spies"},"sequenceIndex":368},{"id":"artofwar-13-16","text":"They cannot be properly managed without benevolence and straightforwardness.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 13.16","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"13","section":"16","chapterTitle":"The Use Of Spies"},"sequenceIndex":369},{"id":"artofwar-13-17","text":"Without subtle ingenuity of mind, one cannot make certain of the truth of their reports.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 13.17","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"13","section":"17","chapterTitle":"The Use Of Spies"},"sequenceIndex":370},{"id":"artofwar-13-18","text":"Be subtle! be subtle! and use your spies for every kind of business.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 13.18","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"13","section":"18","chapterTitle":"The Use Of Spies"},"sequenceIndex":371},{"id":"artofwar-13-19","text":"If a secret piece of news is divulged by a spy before the time is ripe, he must be put to death together with the man to whom the secret was told.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 13.19","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"13","section":"19","chapterTitle":"The Use Of Spies"},"sequenceIndex":372},{"id":"artofwar-13-20","text":"Whether the object be to crush an army, to storm a city, or to assassinate an individual, it is always necessary to begin by finding out the names of the attendants, the aides-de- camp, the door-keepers and sentries of the general in command. Our spies must be commissioned to ascertain these.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 13.20","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"13","section":"20","chapterTitle":"The Use Of Spies"},"sequenceIndex":373},{"id":"artofwar-13-21","text":"The enemy’s spies who have come to spy on us must be sought out, tempted with bribes, led away and comfortably housed. Thus they will become converted spies and available for our service.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 13.21","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"13","section":"21","chapterTitle":"The Use Of Spies"},"sequenceIndex":374},{"id":"artofwar-13-22","text":"It is through the information brought by the converted spy that we are able to acquire and employ local and inward spies.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 13.22","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"13","section":"22","chapterTitle":"The Use Of Spies"},"sequenceIndex":375},{"id":"artofwar-13-23","text":"It is owing to his information, again, that we can cause the doomed spy to carry false tidings to the enemy.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 13.23","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"13","section":"23","chapterTitle":"The Use Of Spies"},"sequenceIndex":376},{"id":"artofwar-13-24","text":"Lastly, it is by his information that the surviving spy can be used on appointed occasions.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 13.24","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"13","section":"24","chapterTitle":"The Use Of Spies"},"sequenceIndex":377},{"id":"artofwar-13-25","text":"The end and aim of spying in all its five varieties is knowledge of the enemy; and this knowledge can only be derived, in the first instance, from the converted spy. Hence it is essential that the converted spy be treated with the utmost liberality.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 13.25","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"13","section":"25","chapterTitle":"The Use Of Spies"},"sequenceIndex":378},{"id":"artofwar-13-26","text":"Of old, the rise of the Yin dynasty who had served under the Hsia. Likewise, the rise of the Chou dynasty was due to Lü Ya who had served under the Yin.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 13.26","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"13","section":"26","chapterTitle":"The Use Of Spies"},"sequenceIndex":379},{"id":"artofwar-13-27","text":"Hence it is only the enlightened ruler and the wise general who will use the highest intelligence of the army for purposes of spying and thereby they achieve great results. Spies are a most important element in war, because on them depends an army’s ability to move.","author":"Sun Tzu","source":"Art of War 13.27","tags":["strategy","philosophy","language:english"],"groups":{"chapter":"13","section":"27","chapterTitle":"The Use Of Spies"},"sequenceIndex":380}]}